Diagnosis of Hidato concerns
These are structural Hidato properties, not pipeline bugs:

50 local_invalid candidates: the SFT-only π_θ (16% Pass@1) emits wrong-value actions (value != next_n) ~50% of the time. Schema correctly tags them as local_invalid. Not a quality issue per se — just that the LLM is weak.

Only 3 prt candidates: Hidato's action space is ≤4 cells with value == next_n enforced. Locally-legal-but-doomed alternatives are rare because most adjacent empty cells lead to viable continuations. This is intrinsic to the env.

30% mixed rate (vs 50% target): a state is "mixed" only if it has at least 1 viable AND 1 doomed valid candidate. With only ~0.3 valid_doomed per record on average, mixed sets are limited. This is structural — narrow action space → few doomed alternatives → fewer mixed sibling sets.

What this means
The dataset is schema-correct and useful, but f_φ's ranking loss L_rank only fires on mixed sets. With 30% mixed in 1500 records → ~450 ranking-loss-active records for training. Smaller than Sudoku's expected ~750 but still trainable.

For paper-final, tighter boundary filtering (skip non-boundary states more aggressively) could push mixed rate to 40-50%. But that requires restarting toy with different params.

My recommendation
Let both toy runs complete (Sudoku ~10 min more, Hidato ~30 min more). The data is correct and useful. Report Hidato's lower mixed rate as a known structural quirk; address in pilot if needed by tightening boundary criterion.